Terminology:
——————————————————————————————————————————
1. project/theme/initiatives: collection of epics that drive toward a common goal
2. epics: large bodies of work that cant be done in one or even multiple sprints. These are broken down into smaller tasks/stories
3. stories: short requirements or requests written from the perspective of an end user
4. tasks: a step in the process of a story (ie: HOW the story will be completed. A story can have multiple tasks)
5. issue: a task/bug/story
——————————————————————————————————————————
Product Backlog: 
	-includes all work items that will be done at some point (new features, bugs, enhancements, etc)
	-includes not just project-related work, but also support or maintenance work, nonfunctional requirements, and research.
	-constantly refined as teams learn new information about the product.
	-the product owner owns it, and it’s their job to prioritize the work items.
	-higher-priority items have more detail in them so that they’re work-ready.

Sprint Backlog: includes the items that will be worked on in the next sprint

User story: a general explanation of a feature written from the perspective of the end user or customer. 
	The purpose of a user story is to articulate how a piece of work will deliver value back to the customer.
——————————————————————————————————————————